[[sn:Right Capital Ward Officer]] [[ja:京職]] [[en:Right Capital Ward Officer]]
<!--Right Capital Ward Officer--><!--Right Capital Ward Officer-->

The '''Kyōshiki''' was an {{ill|Executive (government)|ja|行政機関|lt=administrative office|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Executive (government)|qq=}} under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritsuryō system|qq=}} in Japan, responsible for overseeing judicial, administrative, and policing functions within the {{ill|capital|ja|首都|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/capital|qq=}}. The classical name was "Misatodokoro" (みさとづかさ){{ref|万葉集 16・3859}}. The Chinese-style name included terms like {{ill|Jingzhaofu|ja|京兆府|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jingzhaofu|qq=}}, {{ill|Fengyi|ja|馮翊|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fengyi|qq=}}, and {{ill|Fufeng|ja|扶風|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fufeng|qq=}}. During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, the alternate term "Kyōshoku" (京職) referred to the {{ill|Kyoto Shoshidai|ja|京都所司代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Shoshidai|qq=}}.
Kyōshiki divided the capital into "Sakyō" (左京) and "Ukyō" (右京), with separate administrative offices, '''Sakyōshiki''' and '''Ukyōshiki''', respectively. Their chiefs were titled '''Sakyō no Daibu''' (左京大夫) and '''Ukyō no Daibu''' (右京大夫).
In {{ill|Heian-kyō|ja|平安京|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian-kyō|qq=}}, the offices were situated north of {{ill|Anekoji Street|ja|姉小路|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anekoji Street|qq=}} along the {{ill|Suzaku Avenue|ja|朱雀大路|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzaku Avenue|qq=}}.
== Functions == The Kyōshiki managed the administration, judiciary, and policing within the capital. It first appeared in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}. The Kyōshiki's responsibilities were comparable to those of {{ill|provincial governors (Kokushi)|ja|国司|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/provincial governors (Kokushi)|qq=}}, but its focus was on the artificial urban environment of the capital, a key part of state operations. Unlike the Kokushi, who were {{ill|local officials|ja|外官|1=Gaikan|lt=Local officials (Gaikan)|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/local officials|13=User:Immanuelle/Gaikan|qq=}}, the Kyōshiki were {{ill|central officials|ja|京官|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/central officials|qq=}}, highlighting its distinct role.
For example, while both managed {{ill|family registers|ja|古代日本の戸籍制度|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/family registers|qq=}}, the Kyōshiki handled specific capital-related functions, such as marketplaces, measurement standards, and bridge repairs. Unlike provinces where population management and local taxes were critical, the capital was governed as a hub of imperial administration. Over time, discrepancies between the register and reality grew, leading to reforms like granting Kyōshiki the power to adjust registers in {{ill|Jōgan|ja|貞観 (日本)|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōgan|qq=}} 18 (876 CE).{{ref|市川 2009, P128-140}}
Kyōshiki had jurisdiction over marketplaces through subordinate offices like {{ill|Ichinotsukasa|ja|市司|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichinotsukasa|qq=}}: Sakyōshiki managed the Eastern Market, and Ukyōshiki oversaw the Western Market. Regional responsibilities were handled by '''Bōryō''' (坊令) and '''Bōchō''' (坊長), analogous to provincial officials but selected from local residents. However, with urban growth during the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}, noble households and their retainers increasingly ignored Kyōshiki orders. In response, the {{ill|Bōryō system|ja|坊令制度|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bōryō system|qq=}} was replaced by local figures such as {{ill|Hōtoneri|ja|保刀禰|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōtoneri|qq=}} and {{ill|Kebiishi|ja|検非違使|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kebiishi|qq=}} assumed policing functions.{{ref|市川 2009, P103-113}}
== Structure == The Kyōshiki included two offices for the eastern and western parts of the capital: * '''Daibu''' (大夫): Chief officer ({{ill|Shōgoi|ja|正五位上|1=Senior Fifth Rank|lt=Senior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōgoi|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Fifth Rank|qq=}} → {{ill|Jushii|ja|従四位下|lt=Junior Fourth Rank, Lower Grade|1=Junior Fourth Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jushii|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fourth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Suke''' (亮): Deputy officer ({{ill|Jugoi|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jugoi|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fifth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Taijō''' (大進): Senior officer ({{ill|Juroku|ja|従六位下|1=Junior Sixth Rank|lt=Junior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Juroku|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Sixth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Shōshin''' (少進): Junior officer ({{ill|Shichii|ja|正七位上|1=Senior Seventh Rank|lt=Senior Seventh Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shichii|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Seventh Rank|qq=}}) * '''Daisakan''' (大属): Senior secretary ({{ill|Hachii|ja|正八位下|1=Senior Eighth Rank|lt=Senior Eighth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachii|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Eighth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Shōsakan''' (少属): Junior secretary ({{ill|Hachii|ja|従八位上|1=Junior Eighth Rank|lt=Junior Eighth Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachii|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Eighth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Bōryō''' (坊令): Neighborhood head (unranked → {{ill|Shoshōi|ja|少初位下|1=Lesser Initial Rank|lt=Lesser Initial Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shoshōi|13=User:Immanuelle/Lesser Initial Rank|qq=}}) ** '''Bōchō''' (坊長): Subordinate neighborhood official * Support staff included '''Shishō''' (clerks), '''Shokushō''' (operational staff), and laborers.
The administrative sub-offices included: * {{ill|Ichinotsukasa|ja|市司|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichinotsukasa|qq=}} (Eastern and Western Market Offices)
== Comparison with Tang China == Unlike Japan, Tang China managed its capital {{ill|Chang'an|ja|長安|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chang'an|qq=}} through regular provincial systems like {{ill|Kuannei Dao|ja|関内道|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuannei Dao|qq=}}, which supervised {{ill|Yongzhou|ja|雍州|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yongzhou|qq=}} under its jurisdiction. Additionally, tasks like policing and tax collection were divided among multiple layers of officials. The Kyōshiki's centralized model reflected Japan's adaptation of Tang principles to a smaller, more urbanized environment.{{ref|市川 2009, P216-264}}
== Kyōshiki in the Muromachi and Sengoku Periods == In the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}, the {{ill|Hosokawa clan|ja|細川氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hosokawa clan|qq=}} held the title of '''Ukyō no Daibu''' for generations, leading to the nickname "Kyōchōke" (京兆家). During the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}}, the title of '''Sakyō no Daibu''' became a popular honorary title for {{ill|daimyō|ja|戦国大名|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/daimyō|qq=}}, including prominent clans like the {{ill|Takeda|ja|武田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda|qq=}} and {{ill|Hōjō|ja|後北条氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōjō|qq=}}.
