The '''Kyōshiki''' was an {{ill|Executive (government)|ja|行政機関|lt=administrative office|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Executive (government)|qq=}} under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritsuryō system|qq=}} in Japan, responsible for overseeing judicial, administrative, and policing functions within the {{ill|capital|ja|首都|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/capital|qq=}}. The classical name was "Misatodokoro" (みさとづかさ){{ref|万葉集 16・3859}}. The Chinese-style name included terms like {{ill|Jingzhaofu|ja|京兆府|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jingzhaofu|qq=}}, {{ill|Fengyi|ja|馮翊|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fengyi|qq=}}, and {{ill|Fufeng|ja|扶風|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fufeng|qq=}}. During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, the alternate term "Kyōshoku" (京職) referred to the {{ill|Kyoto Shoshidai|ja|京都所司代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Shoshidai|qq=}}.
Kyōshiki divided the capital into "Sakyō" (左京) and "Ukyō" (右京), with separate administrative offices, '''Sakyōshiki''' and '''Ukyōshiki''', respectively. Their chiefs were titled '''Sakyō no Daibu''' (左京大夫) and '''Ukyō no Daibu''' (右京大夫).
In {{ill|Heian-kyō|ja|平安京|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian-kyō|qq=}}, the offices were situated north of {{ill|Anekoji Street|ja|姉小路|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anekoji Street|qq=}} along the {{ill|Suzaku Avenue|ja|朱雀大路|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzaku Avenue|qq=}}.
