== Structure == The Kyōshiki included two offices for the eastern and western parts of the capital: * '''Daibu''' (大夫): Chief officer ({{ill|Shōgoi|ja|正五位上|1=Senior Fifth Rank|lt=Senior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōgoi|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Fifth Rank|qq=}} → {{ill|Jushii|ja|従四位下|lt=Junior Fourth Rank, Lower Grade|1=Junior Fourth Rank|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jushii|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fourth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Suke''' (亮): Deputy officer ({{ill|Jugoi|ja|従五位下|1=Junior Fifth Rank|lt=Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jugoi|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Fifth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Taijō''' (大進): Senior officer ({{ill|Juroku|ja|従六位下|1=Junior Sixth Rank|lt=Junior Sixth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Juroku|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Sixth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Shōshin''' (少進): Junior officer ({{ill|Shichii|ja|正七位上|1=Senior Seventh Rank|lt=Senior Seventh Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shichii|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Seventh Rank|qq=}}) * '''Daisakan''' (大属): Senior secretary ({{ill|Hachii|ja|正八位下|1=Senior Eighth Rank|lt=Senior Eighth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachii|13=User:Immanuelle/Senior Eighth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Shōsakan''' (少属): Junior secretary ({{ill|Hachii|ja|従八位上|1=Junior Eighth Rank|lt=Junior Eighth Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachii|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Eighth Rank|qq=}}) * '''Bōryō''' (坊令): Neighborhood head (unranked → {{ill|Shoshōi|ja|少初位下|1=Lesser Initial Rank|lt=Lesser Initial Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shoshōi|13=User:Immanuelle/Lesser Initial Rank|qq=}}) ** '''Bōchō''' (坊長): Subordinate neighborhood official * Support staff included '''Shishō''' (clerks), '''Shokushō''' (operational staff), and laborers.
The administrative sub-offices included: * {{ill|City Offices (Tōji and Sai)|ja|市司|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichinotsukasa|qq=}} (Eastern and Western Market Offices)
== Comparison with Tang China == Unlike Japan, Tang China managed its capital {{ill|Chang'an|ja|長安|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chang'an|qq=}} through regular provincial systems like {{ill|Kuannei Dao|ja|関内道|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuannei Dao|qq=}}, which supervised {{ill|Yongzhou|ja|雍州|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yongzhou|qq=}} under its jurisdiction. Additionally, tasks like policing and tax collection were divided among multiple layers of officials. The Kyōshiki's centralized model reflected Japan's adaptation of Tang principles to a smaller, more urbanized environment.{{ref|市川 2009, P216-264}}
== Kyōshiki in the Muromachi and Sengoku Periods == In the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}, the {{ill|Hosokawa clan|ja|細川氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hosokawa clan|qq=}} held the title of '''Ukyō no Daibu''' for generations, leading to the nickname "Kyōchōke" (京兆家). During the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}}, the title of '''Sakyō no Daibu''' became a popular honorary title for {{ill|daimyō|ja|戦国大名|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/daimyō|qq=}}, including prominent clans like the {{ill|Takeda|ja|武田氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda|qq=}} and {{ill|Hōjō|ja|後北条氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōjō|qq=}}.
