The '''Kyōshiki''' was an [[:en:Executive (government)|administrative office]] under the [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]] in Japan, responsible for overseeing judicial, administrative, and policing functions within the [[:en:Capital city|capital]]. The classical name was "Misatodokoro" (みさとづかさ){{ref|万葉集 16・3859}}. The Chinese-style name included terms like [[:en:Jingzhao|Jingzhaofu]], {{ill|Fengyi|ja|馮翊|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fengyi|qq=}}, and {{ill|Fufeng|ja|扶風|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fufeng|qq=}}. During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], the alternate term "Kyōshoku" (京職) referred to the [[:en:Kyoto Shoshidai|Kyoto Shoshidai]].
Kyōshiki divided the capital into "Sakyō" (左京) and "Ukyō" (右京), with separate administrative offices, '''Sakyōshiki''' and '''Ukyōshiki''', respectively. Their chiefs were titled '''Sakyō no Daibu''' (左京大夫) and '''Ukyō no Daibu''' (右京大夫).
In [[:en:Heian-kyō|Heian-kyō]], the offices were situated north of {{ill|Anekoji Street|ja|姉小路|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Anekoji Street|qq=}} along the [[:en:Suzaku Avenue|Suzaku Avenue]].
