For example, while both managed {{ill|family registers|ja|古代日本の戸籍制度|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/family registers|qq=}}, the Kyōshiki handled specific capital-related functions, such as marketplaces, measurement standards, and bridge repairs. Unlike provinces where population management and local taxes were critical, the capital was governed as a hub of imperial administration. Over time, discrepancies between the register and reality grew, leading to reforms like granting Kyōshiki the power to adjust registers in [[:en:Jōgan|Jōgan]] 18 (876 CE).{{ref|市川 2009, P128-140}}
Kyōshiki had jurisdiction over marketplaces through subordinate offices like {{ill|City Offices (Tōji and Sai)|ja|市司|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichinotsukasa|qq=}}: Sakyōshiki managed the Eastern Market, and Ukyōshiki oversaw the Western Market. Regional responsibilities were handled by '''Bōryō''' (坊令) and '''Bōchō''' (坊長), analogous to provincial officials but selected from local residents. However, with urban growth during the [[:en:Heian period|Heian period]], noble households and their retainers increasingly ignored Kyōshiki orders. In response, the {{ill|Bōryō system|ja|坊令制度|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bōryō system|qq=}} was replaced by local figures such as {{ill|Hōtoneri|ja|保刀禰|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōtoneri|qq=}} and {{ill|Office of Police and Justice|lt=Office of Police and Justice|lt=Kebiishi|ja|検非違使|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kebiishi|qq=}} assumed policing functions.{{ref|市川 2009, P103-113}}
